</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,223,248]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</emphasis>
Strongly polysiphonic stems, up to 
<quantity box="[756,837,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="95.0">95 mm</quantity>
high. Branching irregular in more or less one plane. Stems and branches with distinct zigzag.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Hydrothecae alternately arranged in one plane. Hydrotheca tubiform (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1100,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1333,224,1848]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[221,1362,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Modeeria rotunda (Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1827): A, hydrotheca; B, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow). Stegolaria geniculata (Allman, 1888): C, hydrotheca (note geniculate arrangement); D, hydrotheca showing plicate operculum; E, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow); F, detail of distal part of hydrotheca. Stegopoma plicatile (M. Sars, 1863): G, adnate hydrotheca; H, free hydrotheca. Scale bars: Scale bars: 200 µm (A, C-D, G-H), 100 µm (B, E – F)," httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1044780/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), curved outwards, adnate to stem or branch for half to two-thirds of its height (
<figureCitation box="[724,814,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1333,224,1848]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[221,1362,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Modeeria rotunda (Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1827): A, hydrotheca; B, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow). Stegolaria geniculata (Allman, 1888): C, hydrotheca (note geniculate arrangement); D, hydrotheca showing plicate operculum; E, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow); F, detail of distal part of hydrotheca. Stegopoma plicatile (M. Sars, 1863): G, adnate hydrotheca; H, free hydrotheca. Scale bars: Scale bars: 200 µm (A, C-D, G-H), 100 µm (B, E – F)," httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1044780/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). With a basal circular diaphragm (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1301,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1333,224,1848]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[221,1362,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Modeeria rotunda (Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1827): A, hydrotheca; B, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow). Stegolaria geniculata (Allman, 1888): C, hydrotheca (note geniculate arrangement); D, hydrotheca showing plicate operculum; E, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow); F, detail of distal part of hydrotheca. Stegopoma plicatile (M. Sars, 1863): G, adnate hydrotheca; H, free hydrotheca. Scale bars: Scale bars: 200 µm (A, C-D, G-H), 100 µm (B, E – F)," httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1044780/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
). Abcauline wall concave, free part of adcauline wall convex to nearly straight. Hydrothecal rim uneven, with two large cusps, separated by two large embayments (
<figureCitation box="[580,738,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[256,1333,224,1848]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[221,1362,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Modeeria rotunda (Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1827): A, hydrotheca; B, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow). Stegolaria geniculata (Allman, 1888): C, hydrotheca (note geniculate arrangement); D, hydrotheca showing plicate operculum; E, basal part of hydrotheca showing diaphragm (arrow); F, detail of distal part of hydrotheca. Stegopoma plicatile (M. Sars, 1863): G, adnate hydrotheca; H, free hydrotheca. Scale bars: Scale bars: 200 µm (A, C-D, G-H), 100 µm (B, E – F)," httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1044780/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 4C–D, F</figureCitation>
). Operculum composed of two semi-circular, pleated valves, attached to rim embayments and closing as a roof.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Measurements (in µm). 
<emphasis box="[490,621,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Hydrotheca</emphasis>
: diameter at aperture 210–250, abcauline length 1300, free part of adcauline length 500–630, adnate part of adcauline length 800, adcauline length 1430, diameter at free/adnate transition 220, diameter at base 120, diameter at diaphragm 140.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,583,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Millard" box="[322,487,583,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Millard, N. A. H. (1977) Hydroida. The South African Museum's Meiring Naude cruises. Part 3. Annals of the South African Museum, 73, 105 - 131." type="journal article" year="1977">Millard (1977)</bibRefCitation>
believed 
<taxonomicName authority="(Nutting, 1906)" authorityName="Nutting" authorityYear="1906" baseAuthorityName="Nutting" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[597,1022,583,608]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="operculata">
<emphasis box="[597,841,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Stegolaria operculata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Nutting" box="[855,1013,583,608]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Nutting C. C. (1906) Hydroids of the Hawaiian Islands collected by the steamer Albatross in 1902. Bulletin of the United States Fish Commission for 1903, 23 (3), 931 - 959, pls. 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="1906">Nutting, 1906</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allman" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[1283,1429,583,608]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="geniculata">
<emphasis box="[1283,1429,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. geniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, considering that there is little to distinguish them. In her material, she found a variable geniculation, with some branches almost as geniculate as typical for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allman" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[690,843,655,680]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="geniculata">
<emphasis box="[690,843,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. geniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and others completely straight, as typical for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Nutting" baseAuthorityYear="1906" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="operculata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. operculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Vervoort" box="[288,471,692,717]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Vervoort, W. (1985) Deep-water hydroids. In: Laubier, L. &amp; Monniot, C. (Eds.), Peuplements profonds du Golfe de Gascogne: campagnes BIOGAS. Institut Francais de Recherche pour l'Exploration de la Mer, Brest, pp. 267 - 297." type="book chapter" year="1985">Vervoort (1985)</bibRefCitation>
also indicated that both species are extremely similar and was inclined to consider them identical, although he postponed the decision. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramil" box="[793,1105,727,752]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Ramil, F. &amp; Vervoort, W. (1992) Report on the Hydroida collected by the ' BALGIM' expedition in and around the Strait of Gibraltar. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden, 277, 1 - 262." type="journal article" year="1992">Ramil &amp; Vervoort (1992)</bibRefCitation>
, however, considered them conspecific, pointing out that the principal point of difference between the two species is the absence of distinct geniculation in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Nutting" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[328,477,799,824]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="operculata">
<emphasis box="[328,477,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. operculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Other authors have kept them separated (
<bibRefCitation author="Hirohito" box="[959,1122,799,824]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Hirohito, Emperor of Japan (1995) Hydroids of Sagami Bay. II. Thecata. Biological Laboratory of the Imperial Household, Tokyo, 179 pp." type="book" year="1995">Hirohito 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Vervoort" box="[1136,1425,800,824]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Vervoort, W. &amp; Watson, J. E. (2003) The Marine Fauna of New Zealand. Leptothecata (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) (Thecate Hydroids). NIWA Biodiversity Memoir, 119, 1 - 538." type="journal article" year="2003">Vervoort &amp; Watson 2003</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Vervoort" box="[151,460,836,860]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Vervoort, W. &amp; Watson, J. E. (2003) The Marine Fauna of New Zealand. Leptothecata (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) (Thecate Hydroids). NIWA Biodiversity Memoir, 119, 1 - 538." type="journal article" year="2003">Vervoort &amp; Watson (2003)</bibRefCitation>
indicated that it is necessary to have more, and better preserved, fertile material to clarify the relationship between the two species and Vervoort (2006) pointed out that this issue is still open. The material studied here does not allow clarification of this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,943,968]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
This is a deep-water species (
<bibRefCitation author="Millard" box="[845,998,943,968]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Millard, N. A. H. (1977) Hydroida. The South African Museum's Meiring Naude cruises. Part 3. Annals of the South African Museum, 73, 105 - 131." type="journal article" year="1977">Millard 1977</bibRefCitation>
), reported at depths from 253 (
<bibRefCitation author="Millard" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Millard, N. A. H. (1977) Hydroida. The South African Museum's Meiring Naude cruises. Part 3. Annals of the South African Museum, 73, 105 - 131." type="journal article" year="1977">Millard 1977</bibRefCitation>
) to 
<quantity box="[252,337,980,1004]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7269999999999999" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="1727.0">1727 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Calder" box="[351,628,980,1005]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refString="Calder, D. R. &amp; Vervoort, W. (1998) Some hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) from the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, in the North Atlantic Ocean. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden, 319, 1 - 65." type="journal article" year="1998">Calder &amp; Vervoort 1998</bibRefCitation>
); the present material was collected at depths between 
<date box="[1241,1407,980,1005]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1007" valueMax="1942">
1007 and 
<quantity box="[1351,1407,980,1004]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9419999999999997" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="1942.0">1942</quantity>
</date>
m from the Porcupine Seabight.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
According to Vervoort (2006), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Allman" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[544,785,1052,1077]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="geniculata">
<emphasis box="[544,785,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Stegolaria geniculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a fairly common deep water species in the Atlantic and, if its synonymy with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Nutting" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[389,538,1087,1112]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tiarannidae" genus="Stegolaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="operculata">
<emphasis box="[389,538,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">S. operculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assumed, also in the Pacific and Indian oceans.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
